application_type_full: Outline planning permission: Some matters reserved
description: Outline planning application seeking approval of layout, scale and access for the redevelopment of the Green Man Lane Estate comprising the demolition of the multi-storey car park and surface car parking areas, Dean Hall and the existing housing stock (464 homes) and the erection of  706 new residential units and houses (to comprise a net gain of  242 dwellings) together with new and altered roads, car and cycle parking, an energy centre, public and private open space and the provision of a gym, cafe, community floorspace and enterprise units
decision_conditions: The application for the approval of reserved matters must be made to the Local Planning Authority no later than the expiry of three (3) years beginning with the date of this outline planning consent and the development to which the permission relates must be begun no later than the expiration of two (2) years from the final approval of the reserved matters, or in the case of approval on different dates, the final approval of the last such matter approved.   Reason:  To comply with Section 92(2) of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 as amended by Section 51(2) of the Planning Compulsory Purchase Act 2004 | Approval of the details of the 'Appearance' of the buildings and 'Landscaping' of the site (hereinafter called 'the reserved matters') shall be obtained from the Local Planning Authority in writing before any development is commenced on Phase 2, 3, 4 or any other subsequent phase of development concerned.   Reason:  In order that the Local Planning Authority may be satisfied with the details of the proposal as provided for in Article 3 of the Town and Country Planning (General Development Procedure) Order 1995. | Plans and particulars of the reserved matters referred to in condition 2 above, relating to the 'Appearance' of any buildings to be erected and the 'Landscaping' of the site, shall be submitted in writing to the Local Planning Authority and shall be carried out as approved.  Reason:  In order that the Local Planning Authority may be satisfied with the details of the proposal as provided for in Article 3 of the Town and Country Planning (General Development Procedure) Order 1995. | Notwithstanding the provision of the Town and Country Planning (General Permitted Development) Order 1995 (or any order revoking and re-enacting that Order with or without modification) no development to any dwellinghouse hereby approved under Classes A, B, C, D or, E of Part 1, Schedule 2 to the said Order shall be carried out or constructed without express planning permission.   Reason:  To ensure that the Local Planning Authority has control over future extensions, alterations and other works to the dwellinghouses to maintain their architectural integrity and design in view of the limited space within the site available for such works and the impact such works and extensions may have on the amenities of occupiers of neighbouring properties in accordance with policies 4.1, 5.5, and 5.9 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | At the commencement of each phase of the development, details and samples of all facing materials shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to any work commencing on the relevant Building.  The samples and details shall include:  a)	brickwork (including brick panels and mortar courses); b)	metal cladding; c)	anodised metal panel; d)	all window treatments (including sections and reveals); e)	render panels and colours; f)	balcony structures and balustrading treatment (including sections);  g)	metal privacy screen;  h)	metal and timber brise soleil (including folding shutters); i)	metal, cement and render facing and banding detail; j)	glazed and metal/aluminium canopies;  k)	security gates for undercroft car parking areas; l)	entrance gates to the central park; and  m)	any other materials to be used.  The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved, maintained as such thereafter and no change therefrom shall take place without the prior written consent of the Local Planning Authority.  Reason:  In the interest of securing sustainable development and to ensure that the resulting appearance and construction of the development is of a high standard in accordance with policies 4A.3; 4B.1; 4B.2; 4A.3; 4B.8 and 4B.10 of the London Plan (Consolidated with Alterations since 2004) 2008 and policies 4.1 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Notwithstanding the plans hereby approved, full details of the ground floor elevations including:   a)	residential entrances; b)	office entrances; c)	gym and cafT shop fronts; and  d)	energy centre; e)	refuse and cycle stores  shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority before any work is commenced on that relevant aspect of the scheme.  The details shall include: doors, sections, elevational and threshold treatments, all to be shown in context and to a scale of 1:50.    The ground floor elevations shall be implemented strictly in accordance with the details so approved, maintained as such thereafter and no change therefrom shall take place without the prior written consent of the Local Planning Authority.  Reason:  To ensure that the Authority may be satisfied with the access arrangements and the street level external appearance / interface of the buildings in accordance with policies 4B.1; 4B.2 and 4B.5 of the London Plan (Consolidated with Alterations since 2004) 2008 and policies 4.1, 4.10 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Typical elevations of the building(s) hereby approved at scale 1:50 shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to work commencing on site.  The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the elevational details so approved, shall be maintained as such thereafter and no change therefrom shall take place without the prior written consent of the Local Planning Authority.  Reason:  To ensure that the Authority may be satisfied with the external appearance of the building in accordance with policies 4B.1 and 4B.2 of the London Plan (Consolidated with Alterations since 2004) 2008 and policies 4.1 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | A Green Procurement Plan shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority before the development hereby permitted is commenced. The Green Procurement Plan shall demonstrate how the procurement of materials for the development will promote sustainability, including by use of low impact, sustainably sourced, reused and recycled materials, including reuse of demolition waste. The development shall not be carried out otherwise than in accordance with the particulars so approved in this Plan.  Reason:  To ensure sustainable procurement of materials which minimises the negative environmental impacts of construction in accordance with policies 4A.1; 4A.2; 4A.3; 4A.4; 4A.5 and 4A.6 of the Consolidated London Plan (Consolidated with Alterations since 2004) 2008 and policies 2.1, 2.10, 4.1 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Prior to the commencement of each phase of development, details shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority demonstrating measures to be incorporated into that phase to ensure that all residential units have been designed to achieve at least 'Level 4 of the Code for Sustainable Homes' or higher as required by the approved standards at that time, unless otherwise agreed in writing by the local planning authority.  No dwelling within the relevant phase of development shall be occupied prior to the submission of a final 'Code Certificate' to the Local Planning Authority certifying that the agreed Code Level has been achieved.    Reason:  To ensure a sustainable living environment is secured; in accordance with policies 4A.1; 4A.2; 4A.3; 4A.4 of the London Plan (Consolidated with Alterations since 2004) 2008 and policies 2.1; 4.1; and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Details of the gas combined heat and power facility, which shall provide no less 105 kilowatts electrical capacity for the phase 1, with the addition of 225 kilowatts electrical capacity for the following phases, including:  a)	its location; specification and operation/management strategy; b)	flue location, height and design; and  c)	the method of how the facility shall be designed to allow for the future connection to any decentralised heating and cooling network   shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to any superstructure works commencing on site and the facility shall be installed and operational prior to the first occupation of the first dwelling within the development hereby approved.    The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved, shall be maintained as such thereafter and no change there from shall take place without the prior written consent of the Local Planning Authority  Reason:  To ensure the facility is provided appropriately and so that it is designed in a manner which allows for the future connection to a district system in accordance with policies 4A.1; 4A.2; 4A.3; 4A.4; 4A.5 and 4A.6 of the London Plan (Consolidated with Alterations since 2004) 2008 and policies 2.9 and 4.1 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment'  (2004). | The Energy Centre hereby approved shall be installed and operational prior to the first occupation of the dwellings within Phase 1 and shall thereafter serve all dwellings and commercial and community space unless otherwise agreed in writing with the Local Planning Authority.  Reason:  In the interest of securing the centralised energy centre for the site and its sustainable connection to the various uses within the development in accordance with policies 4A.1; 4A.2; 4A.3; 4A.4 and 4A.5 of the London Plan (Consolidated with Alterations since 2004) 2008 and policies 2.9 and 4.1 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | The scheme of photovoltaic panels, which shall provide for no less than 1% on-site C02 reduction as detailed within the 'Energy Statement', prepared by Scott Wilson (Issue Rev6, dated 29/01/2010 and addendum dated 28/05/2010) shall be installed and operational prior to the first use of non-residential accommodation in Phases 1 and 4 of the development.  Details of the photovoltaic panels shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to the practical completion of each of phases 1 and 4 of development.  The details shall include:  a)	The resulting scheme, machinery/apparatus location, specification and operational details;  Should, following further assessment, the approved renewable energy option be found to be no-longer suitable:   b)	A revised scheme of renewable energy provision, which shall provide for no less than 1% onsite C02 reduction, shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to any superstructure works commencing on site.  The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved, shall be maintained as such thereafter and no change therefrom shall take place without the prior written consent of the Local Planning Authority.  Reason:  In the interest of sustainable development and combating climate change in accordance with policies 4A.1; 4A.2; 4A.3; 4A.4 and 4A.7 of the London Plan (Consolidated with Alterations since 2004) 2008 and policies 2.9 and 4.1 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Details of the green roofs, which shall cover an area of no less than 9,150sqm, shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to any superstructure works commencing on-site. The green roof shall be: a)	biodiversity based with extensive substrate base (depth 50-150mm); b)	laid out in accordance with drawing ref: L-P-90-801 hereby approved as part of the Landscape and Open Space Strategy; and c)	planted / seeded with an agreed mix of species within the first planting season following the practical completion of the building works for that phase. d)	efficiently and effectively drained and irrigated to sustain the relevant vegetation  The green roofs shall not be used as amenity or sitting out space of any kind and shall be maintained as such thereafter and no change therefrom shall take place without the prior written consent of the Local Planning Authority.  e)	Evidence that the roof has been installed in accordance with sub-points a) to c) above shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to first occupation of the development hereby approved.  Reason:  To ensure the development provides the maximum possible provision towards the creation of habitats and valuable areas for biodiversity in accordance with policies 3D.14; 4A.3; 4A.9 and 4A.11 of the London Plan (Consolidated with Alterations since 2004) 2008 and policies 2.1, 3.8 and 4.1 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Details of the rainwater harvesting and recycling system shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to any superstructure works commencing on the relevant phase of development to which they form part.  The details shall also demonstrate the maximum level of recycled water that can feasibly be provided to the development and how and where it will be used.   The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved, shall be maintained as such thereafter and no change therefrom shall take place without the prior written consent of the Local Planning Authority.  Reason:  To ensure the sustainable use of water in accordance with policy 4A.16 of the London Plan (Consolidated with Alterations since 2004) 2008 and policy 2.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | None of the dwellings in any phase shall be occupied until all of the approved car parking spaces associated with that phase have been laid out and completed together with the associated access roads and manoeuvring areas and these areas shall only be used for car or motor cycle parking and for no other purpose unless otherwise agreed in writing with the Local Planning Authority.   Reason:  To ensure adequate car parking is provided and retained in conjunction with the development in the interests of the general amenities of the locality and the free flow of traffic and conditions of general highway safety on the neighbouring highways in accordance with policy 9.1 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Details of a strategy for the decommissioning of the existing surface shoppers car park and the provision of on-street shoppers car parking spaces (including disabled spaces) within the site shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to the commencement of Phase 2 of the development and the approved strategy shall be carried out as agreed and these spaces shall be retained thereafter for shoppers car parking only on the agreed days and between the agreed times, unless otherwise agreed in writing with the Local Planning Authority.   Reason:  To ensure adequate car parking is provided and retained for visitors to West Ealing shopping centre in order to maintain its retail vitality and viability in accordance with policies 4.3, 7.1, 9.1 and 9.7 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | None of the dwellings in any phase shall be occupied until all of the approved cycle parking spaces associated with that phase have been completed and available for use and these areas shall only be used for cycle parking and for no other purpose unless otherwise agreed in writing with the Local Planning Authority.   Reason:  To ensure adequate cycle parking is provided and retained in conjunction with the development in pursuance of the objectives of sustainability and encouraging the use of modes of transport other than private motor vehicles in accordance with policies 9.1 and 9.6 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | None of the dwellings in any phase shall be occupied until footpaths from the public highway to the entrance of the property has been provided in accordance with the approved layout and completed and surfaced in accordance with approved hard surfacing details.   Reason:  To ensure a safe and adequate access is provided in the interest of the residents and visitors to the development in accordance with policies 9.1 and 9.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Details of the dedicated refuse / recycling enclosure together with a waste management strategy shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority prior to any superstructure works commencing on the relevant phase; and the approved enclosure shall be provided/erected prior to the first occupation of the buildings hereby approved.    The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details and waste strategy approved and no change therefrom shall take place without the prior written consent of the Local Planning Authority.  Reason:  To secure the necessary physical waste enclosures to support the development and to ensure that responsible waste management practices are adhered to in accordance with policy 4A.22 of the London Plan (Consolidated with Alterations since 2004) 2008 and policies 2.10, 4.1 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | The soft landscaping approved for each phase as part of the 'reserved matters' shall be provided no later than two months of the substantial completion of the phase, or such other time as may be agreed with the Local Planning Authority and any tree or shrub which within 5 years of planting dies, is removed, is damaged or diseased shall be replaced with another of the same species and size, unless otherwise agreed in writing with the Local Planning Authority.   Reason:  To ensure the approved landscaping is provided as an integral feature of the development and retained in the interests of the setting of the buildings and visual amenities of the locality and to provide biodiversity within the site in accordance with policies 3.8, 4.1, 4.5 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | The hard and soft landscaping along Singapore Road, approved as part of the 'reserved matters' shall be carried out in accordance with the approved details and phasing of these works, shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority. Any tree or shrub which within 5 years of planting dies, is removed, is damaged or diseased shall be replaced with another of the same species and size, unless otherwise agreed in writing with the Local Planning Authority  Reason:   To ensure the approved landscaping is provided as an integral feature of the development and retained in the interests of the setting of the buildings and visual amenities of the locality and to provide biodiversity within the site in accordance with policies 3.8, 4.1, 4.5 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Prior to commencement of any phase details in accordance with British Standard 5837:2005 'Trees in Relation to Construction Recommendations' of the protection measures for trees and shrubs to be retained within and adjacent to the phase/site and their root protection areas shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority and the approved details shall be in place prior to any demolition or construction work being carried out within that phase and retained until that phase of the development has been completed.  Within the agreed tree, shrub and their root protection areas there shall be no access and no storage or siting of any materials, rubble, plant, soil, temporary structures, parking of vehicles and no hardstanding or installation of underground services shall be provided within these areas and the soil levels within these areas shall not be altered.   Reason:   To safeguard the future of these trees and shrubs in the interests of the visual amenities of the area and the setting and character of the proposed development  in accordance with policies 4.1 and 4.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | The landscaping details to be submitted shall include details of the design, number and siting of bird and bat boxes within each phase of the development and these approved details shall be completed within 2 months of the substantial completion of the development  Reason: In the interests of enhancing nature conservation and biodiversity in accordance with policy 3.8 of the adopted Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' 2004 | The incidental areas of hard landscaping (other than for providing pedestrian and vehicular access and parking) approved for each phase as part of the 'reserved matters' shall be provided no later than two months of the substantial completion of the phase, or such other time as may be agreed with the local planning authority.   Reason:  To ensure the approved landscaping is provided as an integral feature of the development in the interests of the setting of the buildings and visual amenities of the locality in accordance with policies 4.1and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | The boundary treatment approved for each phase as part of the 'reserved matters' shall be completed prior to the first occupation of the property it is to serve.  Reason:   To ensure that the materials harmonise with the surroundings and the works safeguard the amenities of occupiers of the existing and proposed dwellings, in accordance with policies 3.1, 4.1, 4.5 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | The details of landscaping to be provided as part of the 'reserved matters' for each phase of the development shall include details of the landscaped areas above the ground floor car parking proposed and the measures within the design of the building to support such works. These details shall include :   a)	sufficient depth of soil or  growing medium for the relevant planting; b)	the species and their numbers and density of planting c)	planting within the first planting season following the practical completion of the building works. d)	relevant efficient and effective drainage and irrigation to sustain the relevant vegetation e)	the finishes to the hard landscaped areas.   The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved, shall be maintained as such thereafter and no change therefrom shall take place without the prior written consent of the Local Planning Authority.  Reason:  To ensure suitable landscaping of these areas and suitable structural support for such landscaping is provided in order that visual interest and useful and usable areas of amenity space are created for these communal areas in the interests of the residents of the development and to make these areas integral to the layout and design of the development in accordance with policies 4.1, 4.5 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Details of a management strategy, including the times and nature of access available to the public to the open area within the central perimeter block shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority prior to the first occupation of any part of this block and such access shall be made available within 2 months of the laying out of this area of open space and shall not be amended without the written permission of the Local Planning Authority.   Reason:  To provide and retain public access in the interests of the general and residential amenities of the locality in accordance with policies 4.1, 4.5 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Details of the privacy screens to be provided for the balconies of the flats shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority prior to the erection of the buildings in this development and the details so approved shall be installed prior to the first occupation of dwelling it serves and shall not thereafter be altered, replaced or removed except with the prior written permission of the Local Planning Authority.   Reason:  To safeguard the amenities of occupiers of neighbouring properties in accordance with policies 4.1 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | All of the residential properties shall be built to Lifetime Homes standards and in accordance with the guidance contained within SPG7 'Accessible Ealing' unless otherwise agreed by the Local Planning Authority.   Reason:  To ensure that the development is accessible by all future occupiers, in accordance with policies 4.1, 4.3 and 5.3 of the Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004) and Supplementary Planning Guidance 7 'Accessible Ealing'. | The 83 wheelchair / wheelchair adaptable housing units hereby approved shall be provided as part of the development.  The wheelchair / wheelchair adaptable housing units shall be provided prior to the first occupation of the Building to which they form part.   Prior to the first occupation of the relevant phase of development, the following audit shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning authority: b)	an as built Wheelchair Accessible Housing checklist completed by a suitably qualified 3rd party.  The development shall be constructed strictly in accordance with the details so approved and no change therefrom shall take place without the prior written consent of the Local Planning Authority.    Reason:  To ensure provision of wheelchair housing as agreed, in a timely fashion and to: address the backlog of and current unmet housing needs; produce a sustainable mix of accommodation; and provide appropriate choices and housing opportunities for wheelchair users and their families, in accordance with policy 4B.5 of the London Plan (Consolidated with alterations since 2004) 2008 and policy 5.3 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | All lifts serving the dwellings hereby approved shall be installed and operational prior to the first occupation of the residential dwellings they serve.  The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved, maintained as such thereafter and no change therefrom shall take place without the prior written consent of the Local Planning Authority.  Reason:  To ensure that adequate access is provided to the residential units at all floors in accordance with policy 4B.5 of the London Plan (Consolidated with alterations since 2004) 2008 and policy 5.3 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Details of the rear elevations of the dwellings adjacent to the Western and Northern boundaries within 21 metres of habitable room windows within 19-39 Eccleston Road and 23-69 Endsleigh Road shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to the erection of these properties and the development shall be carried out in accordance with the approved details and not thereafter altered except with the prior written permission of the Local Planning Authority.   Reason:  To safeguard the amenities of the occupiers of these neighbouring properties in accordance with policies 4.1 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Details of the measures to allow the residents of the maisonettes access to the podium amenity space areas shall be submitted to and approved by the local planning authority prior to the erection of these buildings and the detail so approved shall be made available to the residents of the maisonettes prior to the first occupation of their properties.   Reason:  In the interests of the amenities of the occupiers of these family units of accommodation in accordance with policies 3.5, 4.1, 4.5 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Notwithstanding the provisions of Town and Country Planning (General Permitted Development) Order 1995 (or any order revoking and re-enacting that Order with or without modification) and the Town and Country Planning (Use Classes) Order 1987 (or any order revoking and re-enacting that Order with or without modification), the cafT hereby permitted shall only be used as a cafT and for no other purpose except with the prior written permission of the Local Planning Authority and the cafT shall only be open between the hours of 07-00 and 21-30, Mondays to Saturdays and 08-30 and 21-30 on Sundays and Bank Holidays.  Reason:  To ensure the use of these premises is complementary to residential development within the site and to enable the local planning authority to maintain control of the use of the premises in the interests of the vitality and viability of the West Ealing shopping centre in accordance with policies 4.1, 4.2, 4.11 and 7.1 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004) and Supplementary Planning Guidance 10 'Noise and Vibration'. | Notwithstanding the provisions of the Town and Country Planning (Use Classes) Order 1987 (or any order revoking and re-enacting that Order with or without modification), the gym hereby permitted shall only be used as a gym and for no other purpose within Use Class D2 of the said Order except with the prior written permission of the Local Planning Authority and the gym shall only be open between the hours of 07-00 and 22-00, Mondays to Saturdays and 08-00 and 22-00 on Sundays and Bank Holidays  Reason:  To ensure the use of these premises is complementary to residential development within the site and to enable the local planning authority to maintain control of the use of the premises in the interests of the amenities of the occupiers of neighbouring residential properties in accordance with policies 4.1, 4.2, 4.11 and 7.1 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Notwithstanding the provisions of the Town and Country Planning (Use Classes) Order 1987 (or any order revoking and re-enacting that Order with or without modification), the community centre hereby permitted shall only be used as a community centre and/or a crFche and/or day nursery and for no other purpose within Use Class D1 of the said Order except with the prior written permission of the Local Planning Authority.  Reason:   To maintain a community facility for the residents of the estate and to enable the Local Planning Authority to maintain control of the use of the premises in the interests of the amenities of the occupiers of neighbouring residential properties in accordance with policies 4.1, 4.2 and 4.11 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | No development shall take place on the site until a revised and fully detailed energy strategy (to include a cooling assessment) has been submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority, in conjunction with the Greater London Authority. The approved strategy shall subsequently be implemented in full, prior to first occupation of any part of the development hereby permitted.   Reason:In the interests of sustainability and energy efficiency in accordance with policies 4A.1, 4A.2, 4A.3, 4A.4, 4A.5, 4A.6 and 4A.7 of the London Plan (Consolidated with Alterations since 2004) 2008 and policies 2.1 and 2.9 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan 'Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Development should not commence until impact studies of the existing water supply infrastructure have been submitted to, and approved in writing by the local planning authority in consultation with Thames Water. The studies should determine the magnitude of any additional capacity required in the system and a suitable connection point.  Reason:  To ensure that the water supply infrastructure has sufficient capacity to cope with the additional demand, in accordance with policies 2.1, 2.5, 4.1 and 5.5 of the adopted Ealing Unitary Development Plan ' Plan for the Environment' (2004). | Development for any phase shall not begin until a detailed surface water drainage scheme for the site has been submitted to and approved in writing by the local planning authority. In drawing up the final details of the drainage scheme, the provisions of SUDS measures sh
